-- Japan, Malaysia, India, Thailand, South Korea: Asia Bond, Currency Preview
-- B y   P a t r i c i a   L u i
-- 2010-10-21T23:19:51Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-21/japan-malaysia-india-thailand-south-korea-asia-bond-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku and Finance
Minister Yoshihiko Noda will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The yield on the 0.8 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.885 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 81.34 per dollar at 8:16 a.m. in Tokyo.  China: The government will issue 28 billion yuan ($4.2
billion) of 91-day bills.  The yield on the 2.53 percent note due June 2015 was 3.13
percent. The yuan was at 6.6448.  India: The government will sell 110 billion rupees ($2.5
billion) of bonds due 2017, 2022 and 2040.  The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 8.15
percent. The rupee was at 44.35.  South Korea: The Group of 20 nations’ finance and central
bank officials will meet on Oct. 22-23 in Gyeongju, South Korea.  The yield on the five-year note due September 2015 was at
3.75 percent. The won traded at 1,129.60 per dollar.  Taiwan: September’s jobless rate fell to 5.10 percent from
5.11 percent the previous month, according to a Bloomberg survey
ahead of the data today. The government will sell NT$40 billion
($1.3 billion) of five-year bonds.  The yield on the 1.125 percent note due September 2020 was
1.22 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market, the
island’s biggest exchange for bonds. Taiwan’s dollar traded at
NT$30.792.  Malaysia: Consumer prices rose 2.1 percent in September
from a year earlier, the same rate as in August, according to a
Bloomberg survey ahead of the data due today. The central bank
will release foreign reserves data for the period through Oct.
15. Foreign reserves rose to $100.7 billion as of Sept. 30.  The yield on the 3.835 percent note due August 2015 was
3.33 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit traded at
3.1110 per dollar.  Thailand: Foreign-exchange reserves data for the week
ending Oct. 15 is due today. The reserves climbed 2.1 percent to
$168.3 billion the previous week, according to central bank data.  The government will sell 3 billion baht ($101 million) of
28-, 91- and 182-day bills. The central bank will offer 75
billion baht of 13-day bills.  The yield on the 3.625 percent note due May 2015 was 2.51
percent. The baht traded at 29.85 per dollar.  To contact the reporter responsible for this story:
 Patricia Lui  at   plui4@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
